FMRIB's integrated registration and segmentation tool (FIRST) FMRIB's Integrated Registration and Segmentation Tool (abbreviat- ed as FIRST, http://fsl.fmrib.ox.ac.uk/fsl/fslwiki/FIRST )(Patenaude, 2007; Patenaude et al., 2011 ) is a computerized and in the FMRIB's soft- ware library (FSL) implemented ( Smith et al., 2004 ) subcortical seg- mentation tool based on T1-weighted MRI scans using shape and appearance models.
All these brain images have been provided by the Cen- ter for Morphometric Analysis, Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston, USA ( http://www.cma.mgh.harvard.edu ).

For more information about the ﬁtting procedure for the mesh models including the mathematical formulas and al-gorithms the reader is referred to the relevant literature (Patenaude, 2007; Patenaude et al., 2011 )a sw e l la st ot h ew e b s i t e of the FIRST tool used for our shape analyses ( http://fsl.fmrib.ox.ac.
Statistical analyses Statistics were done with the randomise tool ( http://fsl.fmrib.ox.

The mesh outputs were obtained by adding the -surfaceout option to the ﬁrst_utils command, but are based on a multivariate F-statistic because those outputs use an oldvertex-wise analysis method that is no longer recommended for sta-tistical analyses (http://fsl.fmrib.ox.ac .uk/fsl/fslwiki/FIRST ), but can still be used to visualize shape differences (magnitude and direction)and has therefore be applied in the present study.

Furthermore, a volumetric analysis was performed with fslstats, specifying this command with the respective label number of thestructures of interest, which are visible on http://fsl.fmrib.ox.ac.uk/ fsl/fslwiki/FIRST/UserGuide .

Thereafter, the values obtained from fslstats (overall volume of each subcortical structure) were exported to IBM SPSS Statistics (version 22.0, http://www-01.ibm.com/ software/analytics/spss/ ) and independent-samples two-tailed t- tests have been applied.
